## What happened

`DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and all Apple platforms). Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CommonCrypto) never implemented DSA, so .NET has no native backend to use. This restriction has been in place since **.NET 7** — if your .NET 10 macOS builds appeared to work, they likely weren't exercising that code path at runtime.

You can confirm with:

```
System.Security.Cryptography.DSA.IsSupported  // false on macOS
```

## How to fix it

Since you only need **verification** of legacy signatures (not signing), the simplest fix is to use **BouncyCastle**, which is a managed implementation with no OS dependency:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the platform-specific call:

```csharp
// Before (throws on macOS)
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyParams);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);

// After (works everywhere)
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(
    new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Y),
    new DsaParameters(
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.P),
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Q),
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.G)));

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
verifier.Init(false, pubKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**Other options:**
| Approach | Tradeoff |
|---|---|
| BouncyCastle (above) | Managed, cross-platform, no OS dependency |
| Ship OpenSSL on macOS | Complex packaging, but keeps `DSA.Create()` working via `DOTNET_SYSTEM_SECURITY_CRYPTOGRAPHY_USEOPENSSL` |
| Migrate to ECDSA/RSA | Best long-term, but requires re-signing existing data |

For **verify-only of legacy signatures**, BouncyCastle is the recommended path.
